00:37:47.940 --> 00:37:49.903
- [Audience Member] Leon, I'd
wondered whether you'd talk

00:37:49.903 --> 00:37:52.210
just a little bit about your experiences

00:37:52.210 --> 00:37:55.200
in the end of 1956

00:37:55.200 --> 00:37:59.943
when violation of parody was discovered.

00:38:00.851 --> 00:38:03.703
- Ah, '56, parody, parody, yes.

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:08.123
I'm gonna (chuckles) try
to remember what happened.

00:38:14.295 --> 00:38:15.212
I'm really,

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:21.510
drawing a kind of blank as
to the sequence of events

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:25.134
which led to--

00:38:25.134 --> 00:38:27.460
- [Audience Member] Let
me ask more specifically,

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:29.620
when did you hear about
Madame Wu's result,

00:38:29.620 --> 00:38:33.080
and when did you start
doing experiments yourself?

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:33.913
- Thank you.
- What did you know

00:38:33.913 --> 00:38:35.290
about other people who were
racing to get the results

00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:36.766
at the same time?

00:38:36.766 --> 00:38:40.040
- We had the benefit at Columbia

00:38:40.040 --> 00:38:42.580
of having Tsung-Dao Lee,

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:45.520
who was a professor of
physics at Columbia,

00:38:45.520 --> 00:38:49.140
and he was one of the authors

00:38:49.140 --> 00:38:52.621
along with Frank Yank of the notion

00:38:52.621 --> 00:38:56.580
that one of the

00:38:56.580 --> 00:38:59.733
basic laws of physics,

00:39:01.130 --> 00:39:05.580
which we all believe in,
conservation of parody,

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:09.310
might not be actually a valid

00:39:11.860 --> 00:39:12.853
idea.

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:19.940
And there was evidence,
if I remember right,

00:39:19.940 --> 00:39:24.840
from various experiments
to indicate that perhaps

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:27.800
one of these basic, sacred laws of physics

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:30.920
we all thought was certainly valid

00:39:30.920 --> 00:39:32.400
might in fact

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:35.033
not be valid.

00:39:37.802 --> 00:39:42.070
And they gave us, they actually proposed

00:39:42.070 --> 00:39:43.520
a series of experiments

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:47.480
that might test the
validity of this notion.

00:39:47.480 --> 00:39:51.960
One of the dramatic consequence of this

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:54.700
has to do with mirror symmetry,

00:39:54.700 --> 00:39:56.800
that if you look in a mirror,

00:39:56.800 --> 00:39:59.990
let's say one wall of
this room is a mirror,

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:02.130
and all you guys are doing experiments,

00:40:02.130 --> 00:40:03.570
and the guys in the mirror

00:40:03.570 --> 00:40:05.990
are of course doing the same experiments,

00:40:05.990 --> 00:40:07.203
the question is,

00:40:09.698 --> 00:40:12.530
is the symmetry such that

00:40:14.660 --> 00:40:18.720
both the mirror experimentalists

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:22.563
and the real experimentalists
get the same results?

00:40:23.778 --> 00:40:26.767
And 99% of physicists or more would say,

00:40:26.767 --> 00:40:28.817
"Of course, they must get the same results

00:40:28.817 --> 00:40:30.897
"because that's just the mirror image

00:40:30.897 --> 00:40:33.050
"of what's going on here."

00:40:33.050 --> 00:40:36.910
But much to everybody's surprise

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:41.683
and to the wisdom of Lee and Yang,

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:43.393
they

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:48.180
decided that perhaps the
symmetry was not perfect,

00:40:48.180 --> 00:40:51.570
that there was violation
of mirror symmetry,

00:40:51.570 --> 00:40:53.060
and that the mirror world

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:56.750
was not precisely the same as our world.

00:40:56.750 --> 00:40:59.870
And they made that part of their

00:41:02.120 --> 00:41:03.260
paper

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:05.290
which gave rise to the notion of,

00:41:05.290 --> 00:41:09.050
well, can we check this experimentally?

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:14.050
And of course the story was
that when experimenters,

00:41:15.230 --> 00:41:19.010
now full of doubt about the
validity of mirror symmetry

00:41:19.010 --> 00:41:22.240
and went at it and made tests,

00:41:22.240 --> 00:41:24.440
we found out that the symmetry

00:41:24.440 --> 00:41:27.430
between the world and the
mirror world was not perfect.

00:41:27.430 --> 00:41:29.610
That was a major discovery,

00:41:29.610 --> 00:41:32.830
because for 50 years or so,

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:35.457
people believed that the mirror world

00:41:35.457 --> 00:41:37.933
and the real world were identical.

00:41:38.800 --> 00:41:40.330
How can it be different?

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:44.330
But it turned out that it was known

00:41:44.330 --> 00:41:48.040
as the mirror symmetry was broken.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:49.660
It was not a correct symmetry,

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:52.610
and that made a big
change in our philosophy

00:41:52.610 --> 00:41:54.123
of how particles behave.

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:57.453
That was very exciting.

00:41:58.610 --> 00:41:59.950
Every once in a while

00:41:59.950 --> 00:42:04.010
you get epochs of great
excitement in physics

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:07.950
where you're rushing to do an experiment

00:42:07.950 --> 00:42:11.650
and you're not sure you know
what the results will be.

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:15.710
And it's the greatest joy
when in fact it turns out

00:42:15.710 --> 00:42:19.270
that the kind of results you expected

00:42:19.270 --> 00:42:21.760
don't turn out to be the correct results

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:24.460
but something totally
different takes place.

00:42:24.460 --> 00:42:27.350
And that's what happened
during the parody days.

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:31.280
We discovered by careful experiments

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:33.970
that the mirror world and the real world

00:42:33.970 --> 00:42:35.040
are actually different.

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:36.323
There are differences.

00:42:37.316 --> 00:42:41.870
And that was a period of great excitement.

00:42:41.870 --> 00:42:44.540
Now, we're used to it and we understand

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:47.100
the violation of mirror symmetry.

00:42:47.100 --> 00:42:47.933
Yeah?

00:42:48.810 --> 00:42:50.680
- [Audience Member] Professor Lederman,

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:54.410
do you remember, what were you doing--

00:42:54.410 --> 00:42:56.450
- Make a little space
between you and microphone.

00:42:56.450 --> 00:42:58.100
- [Audience Member] What were you doing

00:42:58.100 --> 00:43:00.380
