00:47:54.230 --> 00:47:55.240
I don't know there was some sort of

00:47:55.240 --> 00:47:58.486
honors physics for smart freshman and--

00:47:58.486 --> 00:47:59.820
(audience laughs)

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:00.653
Like sophomores.

00:48:01.806 --> 00:48:03.230
And I think the last semester

00:48:03.230 --> 00:48:05.810
was optics and atomic
physics or something.

00:48:05.810 --> 00:48:06.643
(Leon laughs)

00:48:06.643 --> 00:48:07.690
Maybe that was the most beautiful

00:48:07.690 --> 00:48:10.170
of the subjects, I don't know.
- Right.

00:48:10.170 --> 00:48:11.110
There's a guy behind you.

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:13.728
He's bigger, and I would
get out of his way.

00:48:13.728 --> 00:48:16.100
(Leon laughs)
(audience members laugh)

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:17.330
- [Audience Member] Professor, what

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:19.970
in current physics research

00:48:19.970 --> 00:48:22.410
do you find particularly exciting?

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:24.340
- Now?
- Yes.

00:48:24.340 --> 00:48:25.173
- Oh, gosh.

00:48:25.173 --> 00:48:29.513
Well, I think it's very clear
to me that what, there's,

00:48:31.530 --> 00:48:35.903
we're in an epoch, I think,
of incredible discovery.

00:48:37.290 --> 00:48:38.890
You can take a deep breath

00:48:38.890 --> 00:48:42.030
and sort of sense discovery in the air.

00:48:42.030 --> 00:48:45.843
Part of this discovery
comes from astrophysics.

00:48:47.150 --> 00:48:48.960
You know, there's a new subject

00:48:48.960 --> 00:48:51.056
called particle astrophysics.

00:48:51.056 --> 00:48:55.270
Particles are the smallest thing
we know about in our world,

00:48:55.270 --> 00:48:58.035
and the astrophysics are the large things

00:48:58.035 --> 00:49:03.035
that have to do with
galaxies and stars and so on.

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:07.060
These two subjects are sort
of joined by phenomenon

00:49:07.060 --> 00:49:10.483
that bridge both subjects.

00:49:10.483 --> 00:49:14.650
So, this is a very exciting time

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:17.550
and what will cap the excitement

00:49:17.550 --> 00:49:20.150
will be the new machine
that's under construction,

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:24.473
hopefully will start working
within the next months

00:49:28.937 --> 00:49:30.223
in Switzerland in Geneva.

00:49:31.290 --> 00:49:35.050
The large hadron collider, it's called.

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:36.090
That's going to

00:49:37.070 --> 00:49:39.540
be like a new telescope, you know.

00:49:39.540 --> 00:49:41.000
Galileo, you know,

00:49:42.350 --> 00:49:44.397
made a telescope and looked up

00:49:44.397 --> 00:49:46.950
and discovered the moons of
Jupiter and so many things,

00:49:46.950 --> 00:49:51.290
in fact, started scientific astronomy,

00:49:51.290 --> 00:49:55.520
and this new machine that's
under construction in Europe,

00:49:55.520 --> 00:49:57.971
which is now participating,

00:49:57.971 --> 00:50:02.760
so all the major nations
are participating in this,

00:50:02.760 --> 00:50:07.160
will certainly give us new phenomenon

00:50:07.160 --> 00:50:11.780
and will help us understand
many of the puzzles

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:14.563
that are bothering us right now

00:50:14.563 --> 00:50:17.540
that have to do with astrophysics

00:50:17.540 --> 00:50:21.600
and dark energy and
dark matter phenomenon.

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:23.610
We're in an exciting time.

00:50:23.610 --> 00:50:27.100
I wish that economically we would

00:50:28.400 --> 00:50:31.140
overcome our present difficulties

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:35.170
and begin to really

00:50:39.150 --> 00:50:42.380
accelerate the kind of research

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:45.750
that will reveal what's going on.

00:50:45.750 --> 00:50:47.090
Yeah.

00:50:47.090 --> 00:50:48.830
- [Audience Member] Leon,
when you were a kid,

00:50:48.830 --> 00:50:51.395
was there some experience or--
- I'm still a kid!

00:50:51.395 --> 00:50:53.750
(audience laughs)
- That's right.

00:50:53.750 --> 00:50:55.410
But that started you down the path

00:50:55.410 --> 00:50:58.623
to become a physicist instead
of, say, a Wall Street wizard?

00:50:59.514 --> 00:51:01.560
- I tried Wall Street! (laughs)

00:51:01.560 --> 00:51:02.520
I didn't work.

00:51:02.520 --> 00:51:04.820
Why did I get into physics?

00:51:04.820 --> 00:51:06.298
Actually, in the beginning,

00:51:06.298 --> 00:51:09.940
in high school and early college,

00:51:09.940 --> 00:51:11.513
I was a chemistry major.

00:51:13.140 --> 00:51:16.690
But little by little I turned to physics

00:51:16.690 --> 00:51:20.100
because chemistry was complicated
and physics was simple.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:22.040
(chuckles) So I thought.

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:22.873
And

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:26.670
the physicists in the area

00:51:26.670 --> 00:51:29.360
were more dynamic, if you like,

00:51:29.360 --> 00:51:32.670
and physics had a great attraction

00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:35.600
because in some ways, it was very simple.

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:39.690
You dealt with a particle,
two particles, and so on.

00:51:39.690 --> 00:51:41.653
Chemistry was very complicated.

00:51:41.653 --> 00:51:43.180
There are all kinds of molecules

00:51:43.180 --> 00:51:45.290
sticking out in all directions,

00:51:45.290 --> 00:51:50.230
so I thought physics had a kind of appeal

00:51:51.100 --> 00:51:54.980
because ultimately it
looked for the simplicity

00:51:54.980 --> 00:51:56.870
and try to make the most

00:51:56.870 --> 00:52:00.460
of understanding the
world that we live in.

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:03.900
So, I think that was, for
me, a very good choice,

00:52:03.900 --> 00:52:06.040
is to stay with physics.

00:52:06.040 --> 00:52:11.040
Now, some of my best friends
talk to chemists. (laughs)

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:16.140
- [Audience Member] When you think back

00:52:16.140 --> 00:52:18.920
to the history of mankind,

00:52:18.920 --> 00:52:20.590
can you mention two or three inventions

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:23.320
that were most beneficial?

00:52:23.320 --> 00:52:25.110
- Inventions?

00:52:25.110 --> 00:52:28.730
Well, inventions sort of
implies something that's useful

00:52:28.730 --> 00:52:31.823
like, I don't know, automobile invention.

00:52:34.309 --> 00:52:35.142
That's a good question.

00:52:35.142 --> 00:52:37.870
If I can think of discoveries, I think,

00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:39.963
that's a better word than inventions.

00:52:41.590 --> 00:52:42.663
And clearly,

00:52:46.120 --> 00:52:49.780
the fact that we can
understand so much of the world

00:52:49.780 --> 00:52:53.260
in which we live is already a discovery.

00:52:53.260 --> 00:52:55.280
I think that's important to know.

00:52:56.170 --> 00:52:59.490
We can understand, we can predict

00:53:00.550 --> 00:53:03.540
Haley's comet will appear 2061

00:53:03.540 --> 00:53:06.560
at three o'clock in the
afternoon on Thursday,

00:53:06.560 --> 00:53:08.950
and pretty much we can get it right.

00:53:08.950 --> 00:53:11.950
So, we know a lot about
the world in which we live.

00:53:11.950 --> 00:53:13.582
But there are a lot of things

00:53:13.582 --> 00:53:15.860
about the world in which we
live that we don't understand,

00:53:15.860 --> 00:53:18.110
and the challenge of understanding those

00:53:18.110 --> 00:53:20.283
is very great and important.

00:53:21.270 --> 00:53:26.222
We have lots of problems facing us,

00:53:26.222 --> 00:53:30.370
environmental problems and social problems

00:53:30.370 --> 00:53:32.443
and economic problems.

00:53:35.070 --> 00:53:37.520
But understanding the world, I think,

00:53:37.520 --> 00:53:39.810
and understanding the
world in which we live

00:53:39.810 --> 00:53:41.770
in a thorough and deep way

00:53:41.770 --> 00:53:44.800
is one of the major tasks we have.

00:53:44.800 --> 00:53:49.800
And this is something mankind
has been concerned with

00:53:50.660 --> 00:53:52.460
for a long time, and it's still there,

00:53:52.460 --> 00:53:56.650
that we do have so many things
that we need to understand

00:53:56.650 --> 00:53:58.513
better than we do now.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:03.610
- Okay, with that I'd like
to thank Leon for his talk

00:54:03.610 --> 00:54:05.263
and thank all of you for coming.

00:54:06.256 --> 00:54:09.256
(audience applauds)

00:54:12.222 --> 00:54:15.389
(gentle synth music)

